{"id": "34793304", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=34793304", "title": "Abyss Box", "text": "Abyss Box\n\nThe Abyss Box is a vessel containing of water at the very high pressure of 18 megapascal to simulate the natural underwater environment of hadal fauna living at about below the surface. It is on display at Oceanopolis aquarium in Brest, France. It was designed by French researcher Bruce Shillito from Pierre and Marie Curie University in Paris.\n\nAll the equipment maintaining the extreme pressure inside the Abyss Box weighs . The device will keep deep-dwelling creatures alive so they can be studied, especially regarding their adaptability to warmer ocean temperatures. Currently the Abyss Box houses only common species of deep sea creatures including a deep sea crab, \"Bythograea thermydron\" and a deep sea prawn, \"Pandalus borealis\", which are some of the hardier species with a higher survival rate in depressurized environments.\n\n\n"}
